\caption{a) Three 1064 nm beams interfere at $120^\circ$ with in-plane polarization to create a honeycomb lattice of intensity maxima.  b) We define a quantization axis orthogonal to the lattice plane and decompose the lattice into circular polarizations. The light at site A is primarily $\sigma^+$ whilst the light at site B is primarily $\sigma^- $. The atoms are polarized by a uniform magnetic field B$_0$ at an angle $\theta$ from the quantization axis.  c) The scalar Stark shift creates a uniform honeycomb potential and the vector Stark shift creates an energy offset between sites A and B that is proportional to $\cos\theta$. d) The potential depth at sites A and B due to the combination of vector and scalar Stark shifts.}
\label{fig:Scheme}
